<subSubSection id="0FBA7CCCD71F8159005D657A60F679BC" lastPageId="470" lastPageNumber="471" pageId="469" pageNumber="470" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="49EE2735E9064610D034B4BB745E035A" lastPageId="470" lastPageNumber="471" pageId="469" pageNumber="470">
<taxonomicName id="D8BB267B8A54BE8E2092E48BB58BA58E" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1835" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Nomius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="469" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nomius</taxonomicName>
Laporte, 1835: 144. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="2BB6C4B9F8FFC605294F6E7950E577CC" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1835" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Nomius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="469" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="graecus">
<emphasis id="D52B9F2AD32EE8ED755F9E27ACF7AEC8" italics="true" pageId="469" pageNumber="470">Nomius graecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Laporte, 1835 (= 
<taxonomicName id="AC5A9EE741A0BFBC95B8A5D55BBEAAF1" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Morio" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="469" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeus">
<emphasis id="8E1E731FDEB903D627534BE0E3C4F90B" italics="true" pageId="469" pageNumber="470">Morio pygmaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1831) by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis id="63FDBB55EC73B40367A14C9E574D6458" italics="true" pageId="469" pageNumber="470">nomas</emphasis>
(roving), alluding to the presence in Greece of a species which Laporte believed was 
<pageBreakToken id="51D0DD5B10E13DB5099D5A727D0D579C" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" start="start">closely</pageBreakToken>
related to members of the tropical genus 
<taxonomicName id="E3DC51B96D9819C95168975A247D2E81" authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1811" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Ozaena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3588B17825A0A8C066714AB907132402" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Ozaena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(&quot; 
<emphasis id="1752A8769AF23E46FBB88732CE1C1A0A" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">
cet insecte est 
<normalizedToken id="C4FCA8A23012A7B3D6E5067FB5187E12" originalValue="très-voisin">tres-voisin</normalizedToken>
des Ozaena et
</emphasis>
... 
<emphasis id="4C8F5387D6F8A4C57AD25431A54A44E6" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">
la 
<normalizedToken id="C866BE0B26534DE2867EB85E5A4C97C0" originalValue="découverte">decouverte</normalizedToken>
en Europe 
<normalizedToken id="5ADE4E93FFBB75B0A0DA30D576519721" originalValue="d’un">d'un</normalizedToken>
insecte qui rentre dans un groupe naturel 
<normalizedToken id="3BE68C1D313E9720CBDD96481494CEB9" originalValue="d’insectes">d'insectes</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="A151A29D3A7D7C2C7D03BC22ED640020" originalValue="jusqu’ici">jusqu'ici</normalizedToken>
propres aux parties les plus chaudes du globe
</emphasis>
&quot;) [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0CEB0AD62940648DAB72B57667A5CD" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">
<taxonomicName id="E76B25F485DD23E7BF558F16028340BA" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Aplochile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Aplochile</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1846b: 208. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="371C9BD1E244D9A5396BD3EE8DAEF13A" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Morio" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeus">
<emphasis id="00D596014F59F202BD75C990C638B0BF" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Morio pygmaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1831 by monotypy. Etymology (original). From the Greek 
<emphasis id="FB8EC32AF6C83677F33AD79EC854A640" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">haplos</emphasis>
(simple) and 
<emphasis id="AAAAEEC07DDE16CC9D8B7628B8D1A12B" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">cheilos</emphasis>
(lip, by extension labrum) [feminine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F13099FE4480F9B12251C91ED01D437F" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">
<taxonomicName id="5B34FE9824D210F46FEB01F8BCE2AFB0" authorityName="Leconte" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Haplochile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haplochile</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1850: 204. Unjustified emendation of 
<taxonomicName id="EB2B6DF9D5987B487005A9FCF5943CA8" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Aplochile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A02B1B017E7634305ECC2D8BFA8B6C74" italics="true" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Aplochile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1846.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="52C0BACE266527DA1D3E115D2D1472F1" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" type="diversity">
<paragraph id="F0175115B1011E9C32E7B660138DF5A9" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="896921DDC038B29D35CB53C5D3737CBE" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Three species, two in tropical Africa and one in North America, Mexico, southern Europe, and the Middle East.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FDB63B3335DEDE2253B3A728602508A" pageId="470" pageNumber="471" type="identification">
<paragraph id="4541A5F96231D3E803771D59DD51F5D6" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3A7EFB5D47C553E86E1F95A3BCB1C086" pageId="470" pageNumber="471">
The species found in North America was treated in 
<normalizedToken id="E1FF732497FD9C43A0DA008079D53A1C" originalValue="Lindroth’s">Lindroth's</normalizedToken>
(1961a: 175) monograph.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
